# Tableau Dashboard Build Guide
## Bank Loan Default & Credit Risk Dashboard

> Note: Tableau (.twbx) is a binary desktop-app file format   it can't be authored directly
> from code. This guide gives you the exact data source, fields, and chart specs so you can
> build the real dashboard in Tableau Public/Desktop in ~30-45 minutes. This is also exactly
> how you should explain your dashboard build process in an interview.

---

## 1. Connect the data source

1. Open Tableau → **Connect to a File → Text File**
2. Select `outputs/loan_data_for_tableau.csv`
3. Confirm these field types on load (Tableau usually auto-detects correctly, but check):
   - `disbursement_date` → **Date**
   - `is_default` → **Number (whole)**   also create a duplicate as a **Boolean/String** for filters
   - `credit_score`, `loan_amount`, `annual_income`, `days_past_due` → **Number**
   - `predicted_default_prob` → **Number (decimal)**
   - `risk_segment`, `credit_band`, `city`, `loan_purpose`, `employment_type`, `loan_status` → **String (Dimension)**

## 2. Create these calculated fields first

```
// Default Rate (%)
SUM([is_default]) / COUNT([customer_id])

// Default Flag (Yes/No)   easier to read in tooltips
IF [is_default] = 1 THEN "Default" ELSE "No Default" END

// Total Disbursed (formatted helper, optional)
SUM([loan_amount])
```

## 3. Build each sheet

### Sheet 1   KPI Scorecards (4 single-value tiles)
Create 4 separate sheets, each just a Text table / Big Number:
| Tile | Field/Calc | Format |
|---|---|---|
| Total Loans | `COUNTD([customer_id])` | Number, no decimals |
| Total Disbursed | `SUM([loan_amount])` | ₹ currency, in Crores/Lakhs |
| Overall Default Rate | `[Default Rate (%)]` | Percentage, 1 decimal |
| Avg Credit Score | `AVG([credit_score])` | Number, whole |

Tip: Right-click each → Format → increase font to 36-48pt, label below in 12pt grey text.

### Sheet 2   Default Rate by Credit Band (Bar chart)
- Columns: `credit_band` (sort manually: Poor → Fair → Good → Very Good → Excellent)
- Rows: `[Default Rate (%)]`
- Color: `credit_band` using a **red (high risk) → green (low risk)** diverging palette
- Sort: Descending by default rate

### Sheet 3   Default Rate by Loan Purpose (Horizontal bar)
- Rows: `loan_purpose`
- Columns: `[Default Rate (%)]`
- Sort: Descending
- Color: single color, intensity by default rate value

### Sheet 4   Risk Segment Distribution (Donut/Pie or Treemap)
- Use `risk_segment` (Low/Medium/High/Very High Risk)
- Angle/Size: `COUNTD([customer_id])`
- Color: Low Risk = green, Medium = yellow, High = orange, Very High = red

### Sheet 5   Geographic Risk Map
- Double-click `city` (Tableau auto-geocodes Indian cities) → generates Latitude/Longitude
- Size: `SUM([loan_amount])`
- Color: `[Default Rate (%)]` (red = high risk)
- Tooltip: add `city`, num loans (`COUNTD(customer_id)`), default rate

### Sheet 6   Monthly Disbursement & Default Trend (Dual-axis line)
- Columns: `disbursement_date` (set to **Month** granularity, continuous)
- Rows (axis 1): `SUM([loan_amount])` → line/area
- Rows (axis 2): `[Default Rate (%)]` → line, **Dual Axis** (right-click axis → Dual Axis)
- Synchronize axis: optional, usually leave unsynced since scales differ

### Sheet 7   DPD / Collections Aging Bucket (Bar chart)
- Create calc field `DPD Bucket`:
```
IF [days_past_due] = 0 THEN "Current"
ELSEIF [days_past_due] <= 30 THEN "1-30 DPD"
ELSEIF [days_past_due] <= 60 THEN "31-60 DPD"
ELSEIF [days_past_due] <= 90 THEN "61-90 DPD"
ELSE "90+ DPD (NPA)"
END
```
- Columns: `DPD Bucket` (sort by custom order shown above)
- Rows: `SUM([loan_amount])` (exposure at risk)
- Color: red gradient as buckets worsen

### Sheet 8   High-Risk Customer Watchlist (Table)
- Filter: `risk_segment` = "High Risk" OR "Very High Risk"
- Columns: `customer_id`, `city`, `credit_score`, `loan_amount`, `loan_to_income_ratio`, `predicted_default_prob`, `days_past_due`
- Sort: `predicted_default_prob` descending
- Conditional formatting on `predicted_default_prob` (red text/background above 0.6)

## 4. Assemble the Dashboard
1. New Dashboard → set size to **1366 x 768 (Desktop browser)**
2. Top row: 4 KPI tiles side by side
3. Second row: Credit Band bar chart (left) + Risk Segment donut (right)
4. Third row: Geographic map (left, larger) + Monthly trend (right)
5. Bottom: DPD aging bar chart + High-Risk Watchlist table
6. Add **Filters** as dashboard actions:
   - `city` filter (applies to all sheets)   Dashboard → Filters → Apply to Worksheets → All
   - `loan_purpose` filter
   - Date range filter on `disbursement_date`
7. Add a dashboard title: **"Bank Loan Portfolio & Credit Risk Dashboard"**
8. Set dashboard theme: Format → Workbook theme, or manually apply a navy/white banking color scheme to match your CV branding

## 5. Publish
- File → Save As → keep as `.twbx` (packaged workbook, bundles the data)
- Optionally publish to **Tableau Public** (free) to get a shareable link for your resume/LinkedIn

---

## Why this dashboard structure works in interviews
This mirrors the structure real bank risk/credit dashboards use: portfolio-level KPIs at
the top, risk drivers in the middle (credit score, purpose, geography), trend monitoring,
and an actionable watchlist at the bottom. When asked "walk me through this project," you can
narrate top-to-bottom: **"Here's portfolio health → here's what drives default risk → here's
the trend → here's who Collections should call first."** That's exactly the kind of narrative
interviewers want to hear from a Data Analyst.
